[_Haemophilus influenzae_ is a small, at times pleomorphic, Gram-negative bacillus that requires blood-derived factors for in vitro growth. Strains of _H. influenzae_ may be either encapsulated or non-encapsulated. There are 6 antigenically distinct capsular polysaccharide types, designated a-f. Type b strains (Hib) are important invasive pathogens in non-immune humans, causing, for example, meningitis, bacteremia, epiglottitis, facial cellulitis, pneumonia, empyema, and septic arthritis. Before the introduction of conjugate Hib vaccination in Canada and the US, this organism was the most common cause of meningitis in children in these countries.

The Hib conjugate vaccine was introduced in the US in 1987. Before Hib vaccination, about 20 000 children younger than 5 years of age developed severe Hib disease in the US each year, and about 1000 died. By 2006, the number of reported Hib cases was down to only 29 for the year. Before introduction of Hib conjugate vaccine, rates of Hib disease in Alaska's indigenous people were among the highest in the world (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3713835/). Although no Hia disease was identified before 2002, invasive _H. influenzae_ type a (Hia) disease has emerged, especially in Alaskan Indigenous children: of the 32 cases of invasive Hia disease during the years 2002-2011, 27 cases occurred in Alaskan Indigenous children (18/100 000) versus 2 cases in non-Indigenous children. The median age of cases was 0.7 years; 3 infants died.

In Canada, the introduction of the Hib conjugate vaccine occurred in 1992, following which the incidence of invasive Hib infections fell dramatically, reaching an all-time low in 2000, with only 4 cases noted by a network of 12 pediatric centers across Canada monitoring for vaccine-preventable diseases (http://jcm.asm.org/content/44/4/1530.full). Among 52 _H. influenzae_ isolates from patients with invasive disease in the province of Manitoba, Canada in the years 2000 to 2004, half were Hia and 38.5 percent were nontypeable; only 3 were Hib strains; and one each were serotypes c, d, and f; all 26 Hia isolates belonged to one clonal complex, ST-23 (http://jcm.asm.org/content/44/4/1530.full). Twenty (77 percent) of the 26 Hia isolates were from patients who were 24 months old or younger.

Another study analyzed population-based surveillance for invasive _H. influenzae_ disease (meningitis, pneumonia, and septic arthritis) in Alaska and northern Canada from 2000-2005 (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2600153/). Among 88 typeable isolates, 42 (48 percent) were _H. influenzae_ type a (Hia); 35 (83 percent) occurred in Indigenous populations. Among the 42 Hia patients, median age was 1.1 years. The authors concluded that Hia is now the most common _H. influenzae_ serotype in the North American Arctic; the highest rates are among Indigenous children.

In Canada, of the about 1.4 million people (or 4.3 percent of the total Canadian population) who identified themselves as an Aboriginal person in the 2011 NHS [National Household Survey], 60.8 percent, identified as First Nations (North American Indian) only; 32.3 percent, identified as MÃ©tis (a person of mixed American Indian and Euro-American ancestry) only; and 4.2%, identified as Inuit only (http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/as-sa/99-011-x/99-011-x2011001-eng.cfm). The largest numbers of Aboriginal people lived in Ontario and the western provinces (Manitoba, Saskatchewan, Alberta, and British Columbia). Aboriginal people made up the largest shares of the population of Nunavut and the Northwest Territories .

A map of Canadian provinces and territories can be found at http://www.knightsinfo.ca/mapmenu.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5672904,12. - Mod.ML]
